evidence: In this study we show that a superalloy-like microstructure with nano-sized precipitates can be achieved in a less complex and Zr-free Al 0.5 MoTaTi alloy with a density of 9.1 g/cm 3 (determined by Archimedes method, see Tab. 1). The proposed alloy was prepared by repetitive arc melting in inert argon atmosphere using pure elemental bulk materials of Ta, Mo, Ti and Al with purities of 99.9, 99.95, 99.8 and 99.99%, respectively.

While σ 0.2 increases only slightly from 969 MPa to 1085 MPa, the attained elongation is improved by a factor of four. However, none of those alloys have reached a maximum strength σ p of 1139 MPa, with the highest value reported to be 1019 MPa for AlMo 0.5 NbTa 0.5 TiZr 0.5 , which consists of B2 with grain boundary hcp precipitation.
